crops.origin: Philippine Islands; native to upper Assam, India
crops.presented_by: Arthur F. Fischer, Director of forestry, Department of Agriculture, Manila
crops.description: Seeds presented by Arthur F. Fischer, Director of forestry, Department of Agriculture, Manila. Collected in Bakiling National Park, Laguna. A large ornamental maple, sometimes over 100 feet tall, with undivided elliptic or oblong leaves 8 inches long, white glaucous beneath, and yellowish-green flowers in lax racemes. Native to upper Assam, India.

crops.origin: Java
crops.description: Shimonita. A large, fast-growing, hollow-leaved Japanese variety of good flavor. It is grown from seed and seeds abundantly.

crops.origin: Java; seed imported from and grown in the Netherlands
crops.description: White Longhead variety. The seed of this variety is imported from and grown in the Netherlands, where the seed is not sown before early July, to prevent flowering. This is the best of all varieties of petsai; very sweet and of a fine flavor.

crops.origin: Java
crops.description: Witte Reuzen or Giant Round. A variety grown in Japan which forms a very large round head.

crops.origin: Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Amygdalaceae. Almond.

crops.origin: Caucasus region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Amygdalaceae. A shrubby tree with long purplish branches and narrowly ovate leaves. The reddish flowers appear before the leaves in few-flowered clusters and are smaller than those of Amygdalus communis. The small peachlike fruits have rather dry flesh. Native to the Caucasus region. For previous introduction see 43302.

crops.origin: Native to Turkistan; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Poaceae. A grass, native to Turkistan, where it is found in dry sandy places. For previous introduction see 101979.

crops.origin: Caucasus region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Chenopodiaceae. A desert-loving annual, native to the Caucasus region, with rhombic-sinuate, shallowly incised leaves and small four-angled fruits.

crops.origin: Caucasus region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Chenopodiaceae. A succulent desert plant.

crops.origin: Northern and central Asia; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Polygonaceae. Calligonum (Caput-medusae). Native to northern and central Asia, where it is used as a sand binder.

crops.origin: Eastern Mediterranean region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: A densely branched shrub 10 to 15 feet high, with minute subulate leaves and small, ovate, densely-spiny, nut-like fruits. Native to the eastern Mediterranean region. For previous introduction see 98208.

crops.origin: Turkistan; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: A slender-branched shrub with whitish branchlets and linear-subulate, minute leaves which are early deciduous. Native to Turkistan, where it is used as a sand binder. For previous introduction see 94931.

crops.origin: Caspian region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: A leafless shrub native to the Caspian region, where it is used as a sand binder. For previous introduction see 98209.

crops.origin: Caucasus region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Gnetaceae. A leafless shrub, 4 to 5 feet high, native to the Caucasus, with stiff branches and nearly sessile flower clusters, followed by red fruits. For previous introduction see 79906.

crops.origin: Turkistan; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Fabaceae. A hardy, drought-resistant, ornamental shrub about 6 feet high, with pink flowers. Native to Turkistan. For previous introduction see 73604.

crops.origin: Persian region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Chenopodiaceae. A Persian shrub or sometimes a small tree with a thick gnarled trunk, either leafless or with rudimentary leaves, and small fruits with thin papery wings. For previous introduction see 78481.

crops.origin: Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Fabaceae. A variety with hairy leaflets and calyx.

crops.origin: Asia Minor; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Fabaceae. An erect perennial with oblong-elliptic, mucronate leaflets and elongate spikes of yellowish flowers. Native to Asia Minor.

crops.origin: Interior plain of Cyprus; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Mimosaceae. A deep-rooted shrubby legume which grows abundantly on dry lands in the interior plain of the island of Cyprus. Sheep and cattle browse on it, and the bees make good honey from its abundant flowers. For previous introduction see 88697.

crops.origin: Caucasus region; supplied from the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics
crops.experiment_name: Introduced for testing by soil-erosion specialists
crops.description: Rhamnaceae. An ornamental deciduous shrub, native to very dry sterile places in the Caucasus region. For previous introduction see 33002.
